---
description: Generate Conventional Commit messages
alwaysApply: true
---

When asked to generate a Git commit message, ALWAYS follow the Conventional Commits specification.

Format:

<type>(optional-scope): <subject>

<body>

Rules:
- The first line MUST start with one of:
  - feat
  - fix
  - chore
  - docs
  - refactor
  - perf
  - test
  - build
  - ci
  - style
  - revert
- The subject must:
  - be lowercase
  - use the imperative mood
  - not end with a period
  - be concise (prefer under 72 characters)
- Separate the body with one blank line.
- Wrap every body line at 100 characters or less.
- Use bullet points for multiple changes.
- Never start the subject with "Update", "Refactor", or "Add" unless preceded by the commit type.
- Never output explanations, markdown, or code fences—only the commit message.

Example:

feat(ai): introduce local intelligence provider contracts

- Add AiProvider interface
- Add AiProviderRegistry interface
- Export provider types
- Update README to document the new architecture
- Expand tests for provider contracts